[In summary: As of Sun 27 Feb 2001 no cases of measles have been
diagnosed, other than the single passenger in transit through several
airports in the USA en route to Albuquerque, New Mexico, via airports
in Washington DC, Denver, and Albuquerque.

A report by WBALTV
(<http://www.wbaltv.com/news/27010380/detail.html>) gives a slightly
different itinerary stating that the passenger departed from
Baltimore-Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport on a 7
p.m. flight to Denver on 22 Feb 2011. The same traveler had been also
at Washington Dulles International Airport in Virginia on the
afternoon of Sun 20 Feb 2010.

A 3rd itinerary for the same 27-year-old woman has been reported by
Associated Press
(<http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_17492753

source=3Drss_viewed&nclick_check=3D1>), stating that San Diego-County
and federal health officials are investigating whether passengers were
exposed to measles after an infected person traveled on a Southwest
Airlines flight from Baltimore to San Diego. San Diego County public
health chief Wilma Wooten says Flight 3423 traveled 22 Feb 2011 and
had a stopover in Denver, where passengers got off and on the plane.

A 4th itinerary was reported by AOL News on Mon 28 Feb 2011
<http://www.aolnews.com/2011/02/27/traveler-may-have-spread-measles-in-5-us-airports/>
stating that the New Mexico woman was on a transatlantic flight from
London to Dulles International Airport in Washington, DC, on 20 Feb
2011 is believed to have passed through airports in Baltimore, Denver,
Albuquerque, and San Diego. New Mexico authorities refused to identify
the woman, but described her as a 27-year-old who had never been
vaccinated for measles as a child. Her symptoms were apparent on her
flights and she was diagnosed once she arrived home in New Mexico.
State health departments are trying to contact flight attendants and
any passengers who were sitting within 5 rows of the infected woman on
her flights last week.

More than 10 million people are infected with measles worldwide each
year and U.S. law requires that any cases of measles be reported to
public health authorities.

The final destination in New Mexico of the passenger is not stated in
any of these accounts. And as of Tue 1 Mar 2011 no secondary cases
have been reported. - Mod.CP]

