[2] Taiwan
Date: Sun 27 Feb 2011
Source: Taiwan News, Central News Agency [edited]
<http://www.taiwannews.com.tw/etn/news_content.php?id=1527331>


Taiwan reports 1st case of indigenous measles this year
-------------------------------------------------------
A 20-year-old college student was the 1st person to contract measles
in Taiwan this year [2011], the Center for Disease Control (CDC) said
yesterday. The patient, who attends school in Taipei, came down with a
rash on Fri 18 Feb 2011, the center said. Further investigation found
that the student had received a vaccine against measles when she was
one year old. However, there was no record of follow-up vaccination
after she entered elementary school, CDC Deputy Director-General Shih
Wen-yi said in an interview. 2 days before the rash developed, the
patient visited Pingsi Township for the sky lantern festival and the
Shifenliao area in New Taipei City, she said.

So far, the CDC has tracked 15 people who had contact with the
student, and 2 of them have reported feelings of discomfort, Shih
said. To prevent the disease from spreading, the CDC called for
passengers who took Taiwan Railway trains on 16 Feb 2011 to and from
Taipei, Pingsi and Shifenliao to conduct self-health management.

Taiwan had 12 confirmed cases of indigenous and imported measles last
year, CDC statistics show.

