[3] Australia, NSW
Date: Tue 1 Mar 2011
Source: Mount Druitt Standard [edited]
<http://mt-druitt-standard.whereilive.com.au/news/story/measles-outbreak-hits-mt-druitt-area/>


Measles outbreak hits Mt Druitt area
------------------------------------
An outbreak of measles has families in the Mt Druitt, St Marys and
Rooty Hill on high alert. New South Wales (NSW) Health issued a
warning earlier this week to be on the look out after 8 confirmed
cases in the past month.

Communicable diseases manager for the local public health unit Dr
Vicky Sheppeard said there had been an increase in the eastern states
this year in reported cases of measles. "Measles is one of the most
easily spread diseases and just being in the same room as someone with
measles can result in infection," she said. "Around one in 5 people
who catch measles require hospitalisation."

The public health unit has been working with local hospitals, GPs
[general practitioners] and schools to identify and contact people who
may have been exposed to the infection. Symptoms begin around 10 days
after contact with an infected person. So people need to be
particularly aware of any signs of infection in themselves or their
children during this week. "Anyone who develops these symptoms should
seek advice from their GP," Ms Sheppeard said. "We ask that people
ring ahead to say that they could have measles and ask to be seated in
a separate waiting room to avoid spreading the disease to others."

Children should be vaccinated against measles as one- and
5-year-olds. Adults between 25 and 45 are often susceptible to measles
because when they were young only one dose of vaccine was
recommended.

--
